ide the library, and the class name \\\"Jaxb_implTest\\\" doesn't feel idiomatic or public enough. I might consider rewriting it as a single file. I need to ensure JAXB RI 2.2.3 supports various annotations like `@XmlAccessorType` and `@XmlRootElement`. There might be compatibility issues with Java 21, especially regarding optimized accessor generation and dependencies like javax.activation. I’ll need to create tests with assertions while keeping dependencies minimal, perhaps using JUnit assertions.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Native Image Considerations**\\n\\nI'm pondering whether setting a system property like `com.sun.xml.bind.v2.bytecode.ClassTailor.noOptimize` to true is feasible, especially in a test environment. It seems there might be a challenge with optimized bytecode generation in a Native image, given that dynamic class generation often isn't supported. JAXB RI generates accessors dynamically, which complicates things. I should clarify these details to ensure I’m generating tests accurately and that nothing crucial is overlooked!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating JAXB Native Image Metadata**\\n\\nI'm considering the JAXB native image metadata, particularly the noOptimize property. It seems I can set this in a test environment using `System.setProperty(...)` in the setup method, but it utilizes a non-public implementation property. I wonder if that's allowed since tests should ideally use the public API. However, it might be safer to avoid this approach. Maybe I should look at transitive jars or public JAXBContextProperties, although they're a bit outdated. Inspecting the jar or source could help clarify things!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ekaxcipW57gGLJTCHucUnXpU|fc_03e12e815af3fdff0169ff047ff70881a0b2b4dd531d407496", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/com.sun.xml.bind/jaxb-impl/2.2.3-1 -type f | sort | head -20 && find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-